06116nam a22006375i 9781575066608DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750666087 a10.1515/97815750666082doi  a(DE-B1597)584304  a(OCoLC)1262307260  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a222/.1108152471 aSchlimm, Matthew R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Fratricide to Forgiveness :bThe Language and Ethics of Anger in Genesis /cMatthew R. Schlimm. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSiphrut: Literature and Theology of the Hebrew Scriptures ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1 Introduction -- tPart 1 The Language of Anger -- tChapter 2 Traversing Foreign Terrain: The Troubles of Translating Emotion -- tChapter 3 Imposing Western Assumptions on the Text: Irrationality as Senseless Violence -- tChapter 4 The Hebrew Bible's Prototypical Understanding of Anger -- tChapter 5 Biblical Anger's Associative Networks -- tChapter 6 Biblical Anger and Conceptual Metaphor -- tPart 2 Daybreak after the Dim Glow of the Enlightenment: Approaching the Ethics of Genesis -- tChapter 7 Advances in Old Testament Ethics -- tChapter 8 Ethics, Emotion, and Experience: The Power of Stories -- tPart 3 In Search of A Brother's Keeper: Anger and Its Antitheses in Genesis -- tChapter 9 Ethics outside Eden: Cain and Abel -- tChapter 10 A Land of Limitations: Anger among Shepherds -- tChapter 11 Anger at the Margins -- tChapter 12 Attempting Reconciliation: Brothers at the End of Genesis -- tChapter 13 Synthesis and Conclusion: Hope in a World of Limitations -- tAppendixes -- tAppendix A: The Statistics of Biblical Language for Anger -- tAppendix B: Hebrew Words for Anger -- tBibliography -- tIndexes -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture -- tIndex of Key Hebrew Words -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first book of the Bible, every patriarch and many of the matriarchs become angry in significant ways. However, scholars have largely ignored how Genesis treats this emotion, particularly how Genesis functions as Torah by providing ethical instruction about handling this emotion's perplexities. In this important work, Schlimm fills this gap in scholarship, describing (1) the language surrounding anger in the Hebrew Bible, (2) the moral guidance that Genesis offers for engaging anger, and (3) the function of anger as a literary motif in Genesis.Genesis evidences two bookends, which expose readers to the opposite extremes of anger and its effects. In Gen 4:1-16, anger takes center stage when Cain kills his brother, Abel, although he has done nothing wrong. Fratricide is at one extreme of the spectrum of anger's results. In the final chapter of Genesis, readers encounter the opposite extreme, forgiveness. Here, Joseph and his brothers forgive one another after a long history of jealousy, anger, deception, and abuse. It is a moment of reconciliation offered just before the book closes, allowing readers to see Joseph as an anti-Cain-someone who has all the power and all the reasons to harm his brothers but instead turns away from anger and, despite the inherent difficulties, offers forgiveness.Although Genesis frames its post-Edenic narratives with two contrasting outcomes of anger-fratricide and forgiveness-it avoids simplistic moral platitudes, such as demanding that its readers respond to being angry with someone by forgiving the person. Genesis instead returns to the theme of anger on many occasions, presenting a multifaceted message about its ethical significance. The text is quite realistic about the difficulties that individuals face and the paradoxes presented by anger. Genesis presents this emotion as a force that naturally arises from one's moral sensitivities in response to the perception of wrongdoing. At the same time, the text presents anger as a great threat to the moral life. Genesis thus warns readers about the dangers of anger, but it never suggests that one can lead a life free from this emotion. Instead, it portrays many characters who are forced to deal with anger, presenting them with dilemmas that defy easy resolution. Genesis invites readers to imagine ways of alleviating anger, but it is painfully realistic about how difficult, threatening, and short-lived attempts at reconciliation may be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575066608zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575066608423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781575066608.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK